<subSubSection id="D3E79686FFF8FFBBFF93532AA68CFD8F" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" type="description">
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFF8FFBBFF93532AA4D8FAA5" blockId="7.[111,648,1357,1700]" box="[113,412,1357,1383]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">
DESCRIPTION OF 
<typeStatus id="44467BAFFFF8FFBBFECF5335A4D8FAA5" box="[301,412,1362,1381]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">HOLOTYPE</typeStatus>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFF8FFBBFF93530BA10BFDF0" blockId="7.[111,648,1357,1700]" lastBlockId="7.[674,1211,216,591]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">
Length: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFF8FFBBFF29530BA467FA47" box="[203,291,1388,1415]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" unit="mm" value="6.9">6.9 mm</quantity>
; length of elytra: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFF8FFBBFE3C530BA772FA47" box="[478,566,1388,1415]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" unit="mm" value="5.1">5.1 mm</quantity>
; width: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFF8FFBBFF9053EBA582FA67" box="[114,198,1420,1447]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" unit="mm" value="4.4">4.4 mm</quantity>
. Body surface dark green with greenish shine, partly reddish. Head as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFE6353CBA4BCFA05" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[385,504,1451,1477]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFE6353CBA4BCFA05" box="[385,504,1451,1477]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; labroclypeus more subrectangular and anterior angles strongly rounded. Eyes small, ratio of diameter/interocular width:0.56.Antennal club twice as long as the remaining antennomeres combined and slightly reflexed; antennomeres 3 and 4 almost fused. Pronotum and scutellum as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFEE9500DA43AF943" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[267,382,1641,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFEE9500DA43AF943" box="[267,382,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E.metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but basal marginal line of pronotum very fine and indistinct,widely interrupted medially. Elytra as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFC9C56BEA6B1FF32" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[894,1013,216,242]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFC9C56BEA6B1FF32" box="[894,1013,216,242]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but apical interior angle blunt, apical external angle convexly rounded, and apical border convex. Metacoxa and pygidium as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFD38575FA615FE91" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[730,849,311,337]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFD38575FA615FE91" box="[730,849,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, ratio of length of metepisternum/ metacoxa: 1/2.0. Legs as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFC2C5730A10CFEB0" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[974,1096,342,368]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFC2C5730A10CFEB0" box="[974,1096,342,368]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; metatibia more slender and long, widest shortly before apex; ratio width/length: 1/5.4; the basal group of spines at basal quarter of metatibial length; medial metatibial face with one to four coarse punctures beside the dorsal margin; first metatarsomere a quarter of its length, longer than the upper tibial spur.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFF8FFBBFD595453A68CFD8F" blockId="7.[674,1211,216,591]" box="[699,968,564,591]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">
Aedeagus: 
<figureCitation id="03C6D988FFF8FFBBFCCC5453A6C3FD8F" box="[814,903,564,591]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[113,124,1612,1629]" captionTargetBox="[186,1133,716,1585]" captionTargetId="figure-229@8.[184,660,1124,1495]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 2. — A-C, Emphania nitida Moser, 1911 (lectotype); D-F, E. sulcipennis Moser, 1911 (Madagascar Nord, Montagne d’Ambre); G-I, E. semiviridis n. sp. (holotype); J-L, E. erichsoni n. sp. (holotype); M-O, E. subsmaragdina n. sp. (holotype); P-R, E. ranomafanae n. sp. (holotype); A, D, G, J, M, P, aedeagus,left side lateral views;B, E, H, K, N, Q, aedeagus,dorsal views;C, F, I, L, O, R, aedeagus, right side lateral views. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4525867" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4525867/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">Figure 2</figureCitation>
M-O.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D3E79686FFF8FFBBFD475413A6FDFC4C" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFF8FFBBFD475413A64DFD4C" blockId="7.[674,1212,628,908]" box="[677,777,628,654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFF8FFBBFD4754F4A6FDFC4C" blockId="7.[674,1212,628,908]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">
The species is, in shape of parameres, very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFD4154D3A663FD0D" authority="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi, 2008" authorityName="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi" authorityYear="2008" box="[675,807,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Emphania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semiviridis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFD4154D3A663FD0D" box="[675,807,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E.semiviridis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B2BAA464FFF8FFBBFCCC54D4A620FD0D" box="[814,868,691,718]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFC1854D3A13BFD0D" authority="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi, 2008" authorityName="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi" authorityYear="2008" box="[1018,1151,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Emphania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semiviridis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFC1854D3A13BFD0D" box="[1018,1151,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E. semiviridis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B2BAA464FFF8FFBBFB6154D4A1FEFD0E" box="[1155,1210,691,718]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by the slightly larger body size, the presence of an elytral declivity, the longer antennal club being twice as long as the remaining antennomeres combined. The hook of each paramere in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFF8FFBBFC1F5554A1FDFC8C" authority="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi, 2008" authorityName="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi" authorityYear="2008" box="[1021,1209,818,844]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Emphania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subsmaragdina" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFF8FFBBFC1F5554A1FDFC8C" box="[1021,1209,818,844]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="924">E. subsmaragdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B2BAA464FFF8FFBBFD445536A7A1FCAC" box="[678,741,849,876]" pageId="7" pageNumber="924" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is more abruptly bent backwards and the paramere is more slender.
</paragraph>
